Aquí tienes un ejemplo de código en C++ que implementa lo que has solicitado:

```c++
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>
#include <algorithm>

int main() {
    std::ifstream ifs("input.txt");
    std::string word;
    int count = 0;
    while (ifs >> word) {
        auto pos = word.find(" ");
        if (pos != std::string::npos) {
            std::cout << word.substr(0, pos) << " appears " << count++ << " times." << std::endl;
        } else {
            std::cout << word << " appears " << count++ << " times." << std::endl;
        }
    }
}
```
Este código lee el archivo "input.txt" y pasa cada palabra separada por espacios a una función que contabiliza el número de veces que aparece esa palabra en el archivo. Luego imprime la cantidad de apariciones de cada palabra junto con la palabra en sí.

Here is an example of a Python program that uses dynamic programming to find the n-th Fibonacci number:

```python
# Define the n-th Fibonacci number as a function
def fib_n(n):
    if n == 0 or n == 1:
        return 1
    else:
        return fib_n(n - 1) + fib_n(n - 2)

# Use dynamic programming to compute the n-th Fibonacci number
def fib_dp(n):
    dp = [0] * (n + 1)
    dp[0] = 1
    dp[1] = 1
    for i in range(2, n + 1):
        dp[i] = dp[i - 1] + dp[i - 2]
    return dp[-1]
```
In this program, we define the n-th Fibonacci number as a function and use dynamic programming to compute it. We create an array of size (n + 1) to store the values of the Fibonacci numbers, and initialize it to [1, 1]. We then iterate through the array from i = 2 to n, computing each element as a sum of two previous elements. Finally, we return the value at the end of the array.
